<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="296" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,831,1182]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,305,831,858]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species has been proposed to be endemic to the northern GOM by several authors (
<emphasis box="[1262,1302,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">e.g.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McEachran, J. D. &amp; Fechhelm, J. D." pageId="15" pageNumber="296" refId="ref19080" refString="McEachran, J. D. &amp; Fechhelm, J. D. (1998) Fishes of the Gulf of Mexico. Vol. 1. Myxiniformes to Gasterosteiformes. University of Texas Press, Austin, Texas, 1120 pp." type="book" year="1998">McEachran and Fechhelm 1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Last, P. &amp; White, W. T. &amp; de Carvalho, M. R. &amp; Seret, B. &amp; Stehmann, M. F. W. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P." box="[389,572,867,894]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" refId="ref18676" refString="Last, P., White, W. T., de Carvalho, M. R., Seret, B., Stehmann, M. F. W. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. (Eds.), (2016) Rays of the World. CSIRO publishing. Melbourne, 790 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9780643109148" type="book" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis box="[446,503,868,894]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). However, several specimens (UF 3984, IBUNAM-P9865, USNM 222431) have been collected from the southern GOM and a single individual (FMNH 90092) was collected from the continental slope off 
<collectingCountry box="[328,441,939,965]" name="Honduras" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Honduras</collectingCountry>
. In the northern GOM, this species occurs on the continental slope from the Texas/ 
<collectingCountry box="[1351,1436,939,965]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Mexico</collectingCountry>
border to off northwestern Florida at depths ranging from 
<quantity box="[802,953,975,1002]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" metricValueMax="5.1" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" unit="m" value="405.0" valueMax="510.0" valueMin="300.0">
300 to 
<specimenCount box="[879,953,975,1002]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" type="generic">510 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,831,1182]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,387,1011,1038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">First Record in</emphasis>
<materialsCitation collectionCode="GOM, MCZ" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" specimenCode="USNM 152546" specimenCount="2" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[397,474,1011,1038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
<collectionCode box="[397,469,1011,1038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">GOM</collectionCode>
.
</emphasis>
The description of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Bigelow, H. B. &amp; Schroeder, W. C." box="[854,1211,1011,1038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" pagination="110 - 113" refId="ref15648" refString="Bigelow, H. B. &amp; Schroeder, W. C. (1951 b) A new genus and species of anacanthobatid skate from the Gulf of Mexico. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences, 41 (3), 110 - 113." type="journal article" year="1951">Bigelow and Schroeder, 1951b</bibRefCitation>
) was based on two specimens (
<typeStatus box="[282,382,1047,1073]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">holotype</typeStatus>
<specimenCode box="[388,563,1047,1074]" collectionCode="USNM" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" type="Museum">USNM 152546</specimenCode>
, 
<figureCitation box="[573,683,1047,1074]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1978,2003]" captionTargetBox="[155,1428,1208,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,1203,1953]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 13. Dorsal (A) and ventral (B) perspectives of the holotype of Springeria folirostris (USNM 152546) collected from the northern Gulf of Mexico. Photographs by Sandra J. Raredon, USNM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3909139" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3909139/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Figure 13</figureCitation>
, and 
<typeStatus box="[741,837,1048,1074]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">paratype</typeStatus>
<accessionNumber box="[844,983,1047,1074]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/MCZ37160" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
<collectionCode box="[844,905,1048,1074]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="15" pageNumber="296" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
37160
</accessionNumber>
)
</materialsCitation>
both collected in the same general area, on the continental slope off the mouth of the 
<collectingRegion box="[655,783,1083,1109]" country="United States of America" name="Mississippi" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Mississippi</collectingRegion>
River, in 1950.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="296" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,831,1182]" box="[199,1408,1119,1146]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1120,1146]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is a deep water species that is rarely captured and, therefore, little is known of their biology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,831,1182]" box="[199,967,1155,1182]" pageId="15" pageNumber="296">
